Key Terms

Test statistic

A scalar summary computed from sample data that we use to decide whether to reject ğ»0

Examples: z-score, t-statistic, likelihood ratio (coin example).

The test statistic converts raw sample evidence into a single value compared against a decision rule.

Rejection region (critical region)

The set of test-statistic values for which we reject the null hypothesis.

Defined by the chosen significance level (e.g., 
ğ›¼
=
0.05
Î±=0.05) or an equivalent decision boundary.

Acceptance region

The complement of the rejection region: values for which we fail to reject (accept) ğ»0.
Null distribution

The probability distribution of the test statistic assuming ğ»0 is true.

Used to compute p-values or critical thresholds.

Business Examples & How to Frame the Tests

Marketing Campaign Effect

Question: Does a direct-mail campaign increase purchase rate?

Hypotheses:

ğ»0: Campaign has no effect (purchase rate unchanged).
H1: Campaign increases purchase rate.

Data to collect: Randomized treatment/control groups, purchases within time window, covariates (customer segment, spend history).

EDA: Baseline balance check, purchase-rate histograms, conversion over time.

Test/statistic: Difference in proportions (z-test) or logistic regression coefficient + Wald test.

Website Layout A/B Test

Question: Does the new layout affect traffic or conversion?

Hypotheses:

ğ»0: No change in traffic/conversion.

ğ»1: Layout causes a change (two-sided) or improvement (one-sided).

Data to collect: Randomized user assignment, session metrics, conversion events, time of day.

EDA: Time-series plots, segment-level effects, bounce-rate distributions.

Test/statistic: t-test or proportion test; or regression with treatment indicator.

